  exam: `<div style="padding:16px"><div style="background:var(--surface);border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:14px;padding:16px;margin-bottom:12px"><div style="font-size:11px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:0.8px;color:var(--text3);margin-bottom:10px">🎓 Exam Angle</div><ul style="font-size:14px;line-height:1.7;color:var(--text2);padding-left:18px"><li>Article 3 bills require <strong>President's recommendation</strong> before introduction</li><li>State legislature opinion is <strong>sought but NOT binding</strong> — classic UPSC trap!</li><li>Simple majority in Parliament is sufficient — NOT special majority</li><li>Used for: Telangana (2014), Jharkhand (2000), Uttarakhand (2000), Chhattisgarh (2000)</li></ul></div><div style="background:var(--red-soft);border:1px solid var(--red);border-radius:14px;padding:14px"><div style="font-size:11px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:0.8px;color:var(--red);margin-bottom:8px">⚠️ Common Mistake</div><p style="font-size:14px;color:var(--text2)">Students confuse Article 3 (Parliament's power) with Article 368 (Amendment). Article 3 only needs simple majority, not special majority!</p></div></div>`,
