  amend: `<div style="padding:16px"><div style="background:var(--surface);border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:14px;padding:16px"><p style="font-size:14px;line-height:1.7;color:var(--text2)">Article 3 has been <strong>amended once</strong>:</p><div style="display:flex;gap:10px;padding:10px 0"><span style="font-family:var(--font-mono);font-size:12px;font-weight:600;color:var(--accent);background:var(--accent-soft);padding:3px 8px;border-radius:8px;white-space:nowrap">5th Amendment, 1955</span><span style="font-size:13px;color:var(--text2)">Added the requirement that President must refer the bill to the State Legislature and specify a time limit for giving opinion</span></div></div></div>`,
  trivia: `<div style="padding:16px"><div style="background:var(--surface);border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:14px;padding:16px"><ul style="font-size:14px;line-height:1.9;color:var(--text2);padding-left:18px"><li>🗺️ Since independence, Article 3 has been used to create <strong>8 new states</strong> — most recently Telangana in 2014</li><li>⚡ India had 14 states at independence. Now it has 28 states and 8 UTs</li><li>🏔️ Uttarakhand was originally called "Uttaranchal" when carved from UP in 2000 — renamed in 2007 using Article 3</li><li>📊 The States Reorganisation Commission (1953-55) used Article 3 to completely redraw India's map on linguistic lines</li></ul></div></div>`,
  official: `<div style="padding:16px"><div style="font-family:var(--font-mono);font-size:13px;line-height:1.8;color:var(--text2);background:var(--bg2);border-radius:8px;padding:14px;border-left:3px solid var(--accent);margin-bottom:16px"><strong>Article 3. Formation of new States and alteration of areas, boundaries or names of existing States —</strong><br><br>Parliament may by law—<br>(a) form a new State by separation of territory from any State or by uniting two or more States or parts of States or by uniting any territory to a part of any State;<br>(b) increase the area of any State;<br>(c) diminish the area of any State;<br>(d) alter the boundaries of any State;<br>(e) alter the name of any State.</div><div style="background:var(--surface);border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:14px;padding:14px"><div style="font-size:11px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:0.8px;color:var(--text3);margin-bottom:8px">Plain English</div><p style="font-size:13px;line-height:1.7;color:var(--text2)">Parliament can create new states, merge states, increase/decrease state areas, change boundaries, and rename states — but must ask the concerned state legislature for its opinion first (though the opinion is not binding).</p></div></div>`
